05035nam a22007935i 9780231542524DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016042344  a(OCoLC)984657847  a97802315425247 a10.7312/hanl177622doi  a(DE-B1597)480265  a(OCoLC)967791348  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aDT154.A4bH375 2017 4aDT154.A4bH375 2019 7aHIS0370002bisacsh04a962.12231 aHanley, Will, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIdentifying with Nationality :bEuropeans, Ottomans, and Egyptians in Alexandria /cWill Hanley. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (432 p.) :b10 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Studies in International and Global History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tTables -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Nationality Grasped -- tPart I. Settings -- t1. Vulgar Cosmopolitanism -- t2. Keywords -- tPart II. Means -- t3. Papers -- t4. Census -- t5. Money -- t6. Marriage -- tPart III. Other Nationalities -- t7. Europeans -- t8. Foreigners -- t9. Protégés -- t10. Bad Subjects -- t11. Ottomans -- t12. Locals -- tEpilogue: Egyptians in the Era of Universal Nationality -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNationality is the most important legal mechanism sorting and classifying the world's population today. An individual's place of birth or naturalization determines where he or she can and cannot be and what he or she can and cannot do. Although this system may appear universal, even natural, Will Hanley shows that it arose just a century ago. In Identifying with Nationality, he uses the Mediterranean city of Alexandria to develop a genealogy of the nation and the formation of the modern national subject.Alexandria in 1880 was an immigrant boomtown ruled by dozens of overlapping regimes. On its streets and in its police stations and courtrooms, people were identified by name, occupation, place of origin, sect, physical description, and other attributes. Yet by 1914, before nationalist calls for independence and decolonization had become widespread, nationality had become the defining category of identification, and nationality laws came to govern Alexandria's population. Identifying with Nationality traces the advent of modern citizenship to multinational, transimperial settings such as turn-of-the-century colonial Alexandria, where ordinary people abandoned old identifiers and grasped nationality as the best means to access the protections promised by expanding states. The result was a system that continues to define and divide people through status, mobility, and residency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCitizenshipzEgyptzAlexandriaxHistory. 0aGroup identityzEgyptzAlexandriaxHistory. 0aNationalismzEgyptzAlexandriaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311054330808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2017z9783110547764oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/hanl1776240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231542524423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231542524/original  a978-3-11-054330-8  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-062526-4  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017b2017  a